A hui hou to Councilmember Heidi Tsuneyoshi, an outstanding leader and good friend to me.

She helped me a great deal over the last two years while we served on the council together.

She was the vice chair of the Committee on Parks and Community Services, a committee I chaired, and I was her vice chair when she chaired the Committee on Public Safety.  We worked to improve our parks, and help to build our public safety divisions including HPD, HFD, EMS and Ocean Safety.

I have learned a great deal from her and she will be very missed! I know her constituents will miss her too.

Hawaii’s economic challenges that grew over the pandemic have had an impact on all of us, but what many of us don’t realize is that our animals are hurting, too. Many families have left their animals at the Hawaiian Humane Society because they no longer have the money to care for them.

We’ve just learned that this week has reached a critical point for the Hawaiian Humane Society.  They are asking all of you dog lovers out there, to help letting one of their dogs “crash” on your couch for between 72 hours and two weeks. Their program, Couch Crashers, gives the dogs a break from the shelter and provides them with a nice temporary home. That also gives the Hawaiian Humane Society more room to take care of the high volume of dogs needing their specialized services every day. 

And if you want to adopt an animal, February is a great time to do so! The Valentines special goes until February 19, which means adoption fees for all animals are $14 – including dogs of all ages! 

Learn more about Couch Crashers at this link HawaiianHumane.org/Couch-Crashers
and see all the animals available for adoption at HawaiianHumane.org

Or come meet them in person at the Mōʻiliʻili campus. Please consider sharing your heart and home with an animal in the shelter, like my family has! Mahalo!

Today, the Honolulu City Council honored Rowland “Ski” Loeschke. He’s an Ewa Beach resident, and actually my neighbor! All these years, I didn’t realize the outstanding work he has been quietly doing in our community. Fourteen years ago, Ski established the “Sharing Aloha'' program.

Every Sunday during football season, he holds a gathering to thank and honor active military, veterans and their families for their service. Over the years, 75 to 150 people attend the events each week held at the U.S. Coast Guard Hideaway Club. Ski buys, cooks and serves all the food. Those who know Ski say he’s become a legend in the military community across the country, known far and wide for his generosity, kindness and Aloha spirit. Before retiring from the United States Air Force, Ski worked for 42 years in Information Systems Technology management at Hickam Air Force Base. 

A big mahalo to Ski for all he’s done for our community!

The pistol & rifle ranges at the Koko Head Shooting Complex will be reopening on Saturday, April 29, 2023. 

While shooting will resume on these public ranges, current staffing levels (due to non-medical resignations), existing conditions at KHSC, and the anticipated high demand for this popular outdoor range will result in temporary changes to operations for the firearm ranges:

• Pistol and rifles ranges will operate as one firing line, due to damaged separation wall
• Firearm ranges open on weekends, Saturdays & Sundays, from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m.
• Free online reservations required to book 1 hour 20-minute shooting slot:
o Conducted online using the pros.hnl.info website
o Reservations open five days in advance at 8 a.m. (HST). For instance, on opening day (April 29), reservations will be available beginning 8 a.m. Monday, April 24 
o One non-transferable reservation per person, per day for both ranges
o Photo identification and proof of reservation required (on phone or printed)

o Five timeslots available for 18 pistol and 27 rifle firing lanes: 
- 8 a.m. – 9:20 a.m.
- 9:35 a.m. – 10:55 a.m. 
- 11:10 a.m. – 12:30 p.m.
- 12:45 p.m. – 2:05 p.m.
- 2:20 p.m. – 3:40 p.m.

o Three rifle and two pistol firing lanes will be made available for walk-ins, those unable to secure a reservation, and those without computer / internet access.
o Each shooting timeslot will consist of three shooting relays and two ceasefires, with 15-minutes between each of the five timeslots 

• No eating, drinking or smoking allowed on the firing line
• More stringent, regular cleaning protocols to remove lead particles from surfaces near the firing lines 
• No metal targets or .50 caliber BMG allowed 
• Pistol targets may be placed at 25 or 50 yards
• Rifle targets may be placed at 50 or 100 yards

Much, much more information is available online at the complex's dedicated website: bit.ly/kokoheadrange

Congratulations to Nealson Manutai, a 5th grader at Lāʻie Elementary School, who was honored at the Honolulu City Council today, after he won the 2023 Drive, Chip and Putt championship.

Held in partnership with the Masters Tournament, the PGA of America, and the USGA, the Drive, Chip and Putt is a national youth development program that is open to boys and girls from ages 7 to 15 where the top three local qualifiers advance to the sub-regional qualifying round, The top two participants then advancing to the regional competition in the National Finals at the home of the Masters. 

A Lāʻie resident, Nealson started golfing at 4-years-old, when his father took him to play at Kahuku Golf Course.  Through hard work and dedication, Nealson has honed his skills over the years, currently boasting a handicap index of five. Prior to the 2023 Nationals, Nealson had attempted to qualify four times. His accomplishments – not only qualifying but also attaining the championship title – demonstrate the power of patience and perseverance.

The Honolulu City Council honored Ewa Beach resident Alim Shabazz today. Alim is the founder of Fathers Fitness, which worked with the Veterans Administration to create the first adaptive fitness clinic in Hawaii for veterans wanting to be physically fit. He also founded the Big Tire Bootcamp, which offers underserved populations a safe environment to take charge of their health. 

His advocacy for his community doesn’t end there. He’s a leader in the local Boy Scouts of America organization and served as the Chairman of the Boy Scouts of America's Onizuka Day of Exploration. He supports the Sea Scouts program, a collaboration between the Coast Guard Auxiliary and the Boy Scouts of America, serving as the District Staff Officer.

He founded Epic Badges, a non-profit dedicated to helping Boy Scouts obtain merit badges. A certified lifeguard and a paddleboard Instructor, Alim Shabazz helps both Boy Scouts and adaptive athletes experience paddle boarding while emphasizing safety and proper technique. In addition, he serves as a Barbers Point Post Commander with West Oahu Veterans Center AM-VETS. 

As a passionate supporter of small businesses, Alim is the Hawaii Chair of the SCORE, a non-profit under the SBA that mentors small business owners.

Alim also is an accomplished professional athlete, fitness competitor, and Master Trainer who has won 16 bodybuilding and physique championships and holds two Guinness World Records for the heaviest total weight for dumbbell curls in one minute. A big mahalo to Alim for his dedication and service to the community.

When someone ends up in the hospital, it doesn’t just affect the patient…family, friends, co-workers…the list goes on and on.  Many lives are affected until that person recovers.  Worrying about whether there is enough blood on the shelves for the treatment they need shouldn’t be another worry on their already long list of concerns.
*
We know you hear our constant cries for help, but it’s no joke.  On a regular basis, we need 150-200 donors coming through our doors on a daily basis.  But this month alone, there have been more than 5 days where 200+ blood products were shipped out to our local hospitals.  The need for blood has been skyrocketing, but blood donations have sadly been down due to people making other plans that do not involve donating blood.  While many people are on summer break, the need for blood sadly never stops.
 *
Please consider carving out just one hour of your time to help save lives in our community.  Your donation goes even further this summer.  From June through August, every time you donate blood, Blood Bank of Hawaii will donate to the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts of Hawaii.  By learning the value of taking risks, feeling confident in their abilities, and teaming up with others for the benefit of everyone, The Boy Scouts & Girl Scouts help Hawaii’s kids reach their full potential as good citizens and thoughtful leaders.  When you donate blood this summer, you’re not just supporting Blood Bank of Hawaii’s vital mission to provide a safe supply of blood to the people of our state, you’re helping to shape a better future for all of Hawaii #EwaBeach #Ewa

The Boot Memorial originally recognized the names and faces of all who lost their lives through combat in service to our country since September 11, 2001. Over the years the display has grown to also include first responders and service members lost in training accidents. 

Theresa Johnson is an Army spouse and advocate for the military community who launched the Boot Memorial in 2012 after seeing the impact of PTSD and combat trauma firsthand. 

Candice Ualesi has been an instrumental volunteer in creating the Boot Memorial since 2013. She has spent over 4,000 hours researching names and photos of the fallen that are affixed to each boot. 

Francine Love has been a volunteer for the Boot Memorial for the past 10 years and has worked to help to keep the names and stories alive by sharing with the visitors daily.

After attending The Boot Memorial Ceremony at Pearl Harbor today, I was honored to present all three of them with the Honolulu City Council District 9 Community Star Award for being a positive role model for our community.
 
The boots are on display from sunup to sundown through September 12th. The display is free and open to those with base access and provides an opportunity to pay tribute to our fallen heroes, support their families, and let them know that their sacrifices will not be forgotten.

The cost to send a team to the Continental U.S. is prohibitive, so in conjunction with staff, volunteers and sponsors from various Veteran Service Organizations, Hawaii veterans opted to organize their very first own Hawaii Veterans Rehab Games at the West Oahu Veterans Center in Ewa.

The games, which aim to bring veterans together, build camaraderie and help veterans overcome isolation, mimic the VA National Games annually held in various cities across the U.S. Mainland. 
*
Congratulations to the organizers and as many as 80 veterans participating!

I recently presented Mid-Town Radio/Disco Mart with an honorary certificate from the Honolulu City Council on its 76th anniversary year. Sadly, the owners, Marge Funasaki and Eunice Soeda, have just announced the store's closure, because they are retiring. The closure of their store is a big loss for their loyal clients and the community, but they have certainly earned their retirement after working there for 50 years!
*
Their parents, Toshio and Yoshiko Yamamoto, immigrated from Japan to work at the Waipahu Sugar Mill, and later opened what was then a small radio repair and electronics shop on Depot Road, just a few blocks away from the mill. They started the business to create a better life for their family and to serve the people of Waipahu. At the time, radio was the dominant media and their store provided a valuable radio repair service. In 1972, Toshio Yamamoto added a second location, Disco Mart, and began selling furniture as well as appliances and electronics. For a time, they were the only furniture and appliance store in West Oahu.
*
The family has always supported their community by caring for, and providing quality furniture and appliances to, multiple generations of island families. They donated appliances and furniture items for church auctions, non-profit groups, the Waipahu High School Athletic Department and other organizations over the years to help with their community fundraising efforts. Their store closes February 29th and will certainly be missed.
